Recapping the Screen Reader Experience

01
On this page
  1. Accessibility Information in the Date Picker Buttons
  2. Interactivity Quirks in Screen Readers

Keyboard and screen readers work together like best friends. When we make our web applications work well for the keyboard, this also helps a lot with screen reader support.

In the Semantic Markup with HTML & ARIA workshop, we talk a lot about the significance of ARIA to the screen reader experience. ARIA provides additional accessibility information about the roles, states, and properties that screen readers rely on, both built into native HTML elements as well as bolted-on ARIA attributes.

In this section, we’ll examine how the interactive parts of the CampSpots app currently work with VoiceOver on Mac and NVDA on Windows. Keep in mind there are other popular screen readers that are worthy of testing depending on your audience’s most-used browsers.

Accessibility Information in the Date Picker Buttons

Being able to focus and operate the date picker with the keyboard is the first piece of the puzzle for good screen reader support.

We can examine the date picker in DevTools to see what other accessibility information is available.

In the “Accessibility” pane, we can see that a date has an ARIA role of button, which it received implicitly since we used button elements in our component.

The aria-label attribute supplies both the name of the month and the number for that day. In the screenshot below, the ARIA label is “August 7” even though the button’s text content is only the number. Visually looking at the date picker, we have the context that we are looking at a calendar. Adding the month to the aria-label allows us to provide additional context for screen reader users who can’t see the screen as well.

Interactivity Quirks in Screen Readers

Some screen readers have additional functionality to try to enable interactivity for interfaces that weren’t written with accessibility in mind. The issue here is that depending on the interface, click events might be added onto non-focusable elements without accessible information or functionality. When debugging, you might run into scenarios where random elements are announced as “clickable” even though they aren’t intended to be interactive in a screen reader.

For example, think of a clickable card component marked up as a div with a click event, with a link or button element inside.

The screen reader might announce that a card is clickable, even though the intended target is an interactive child element nested inside of the card. This may or may not be a problem from a user impact perspective. To clear up confusion, test patterns with people who rely on screen readers every day.
